Reference-contexts: Unlinkability means that independently observed messages seem uncorrelated even when they comprise a single logical traffic stream. Unlinkability only makes sense when the semantics of the message flows do not require a priori correlations, so unlinkability must always be considered with respect a certain granularity. For example, TCP <ref> [Pos81c] </ref> streams require recipients to acknowledge sent data. Therefore, if an eavesdropper knows that a certain outbound flow comprises a TCP stream, then they will rightly expect to observe (at least) an inbound flow of acknowledgments.
